"A generation protesting" in Ethiopia, Long an ally of the USA
Violent Protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators who demand political changes in Ethiopia were met with violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say that tens of protesters were killed during the clashes with the police in the exchange of fire.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a solid ally of the West with a rapidly growing economy.
But in recent months, protests against the government have shaken the country and expanded into more and more territories.
Last week, thousands of people stormed onto the streets and demanded fundamental political changes.
According to human rights organizations, the government's response has been ruthless.
Witnesses said that police shot and killed riots on tens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video circulating about the protests that are probably from last or earlier this year shows security guards beat young people with sticks while they have been forced to make a handstand against a wall.
The head of the UN Human Rights authority is now demanding an in-depth investigation.
"It has always been difficult to keep this country together and it will become even more difficult in the future," said Rashid Abdi, project leader of the Horn of Africa of the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa after Nigeria and its stability is appreciated by the West.
American military and intelligence services are working closely with the Ethiopians to fight terrorist droughts beyond the region, especially in Somalia. Few countries in Africa, if anything, receive so much Western help.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a considerable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
The streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
Even if Ethiopia was anything but a model for democracy - human rights organisations have continuously led the government's repression - the opposition in the country has been restricted, with dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were sent into exile or imprisoned, killed or driven into the vastness of the desert.
But that could change.
"If you suppress people and they have no other options except to protest, it breaks out," said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in Central Ethiopia.
The whole youth is protesting.
A generation protests.
There are numerous complaints that cover everything from land use to the stranglehold regarding the power of the ruling coalition.
After a widely criticised election last year, the ruling party and its allies received the last seat of the opposition and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are rising; a struggle for this jagged, controversial line demanded hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, could take advantage of the turbulence and arm themselves again.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness explode after years of simmering under the surface are now exploding.
The first seems harmless: smartphones.
Only in recent years have many Ethiopians been able to communicate via social media, as cheaper smartphones became more and more frequent and Internet services improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does at regular intervals, especially in protests, many people can still communicate via Internet proxies that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said they were gathering for protests.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
Since eons, the Amharas, who come from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands, prospered in politics and economy, while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowlands.
But that is also changing.
"We are in the process of coordinating under one screen," said Mulatu Gemechu, a leader of the Oromos.
The greatest protests took place in areas of the Amhara and Oromos.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which make up around 6 percent of the population and which are dominant in the military, in intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr. Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death on a non-publicized illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could think about corners.
Analysts say that he was particularly well versed in perceiving early signs of dissatisfaction and using special representative to work on opponents and making them harmless.
