Kepler measures rotational rate of stars in the cluster of the Pleiades
The latest mission with the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete catalogue of rotation rates under the stars of the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers to understand why star clusters rotate at different rates and where the rotational periods are related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other clusters, we learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a press release.
The cluster of the Pleiades is 445 light years away from Earth.
Many stars in this cluster of stars, which were formed around 125 million years ago, now reach adulthood.
They are now spinning fastest.
These ripening stars emit large amounts of stellar winds at peak rotation rates.
Since these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
When a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by recognizing the time between the appearance of a recognizable star spot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalogue of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars are turning slower than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars with dancers, with larger stars turning slower pirouettes than smaller ones.
"In the "Ballet" of the Pleiades we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars," said Rebull.
Since the star cluster of the Pleiades is so close, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The Cluster of Star of the Pleiades provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older," said Rebull.
There is still a lot to find out what we want to learn more about how, when and why stars slow their rotation rates and hang their "dance shoes", so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues have reported in detail in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the Pleiades rotation rates, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
